---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---
<Base title="Leaves.PH · methodology" pathname="/methodology">
  <article class="max-w-prose mx-auto px-5 sm:px-8 pt-12 pb-16 text-ink-700 leading-[1.7]">
    <p class="kicker mb-4">SECTION 1 &middot; METHOD</p>
    <h1 class="font-display font-medium tracking-tight text-ink-900 mb-3" style="font-size: clamp(2rem, 4.5vw, 3rem); line-height: 1.05;">How Leaves.PH measures Metro Manila tree cover.</h1>
    <p class="text-sm text-ink-500 mb-10 max-w-narrow">Current scope: the 17 NCR LGUs (16 cities + Pateros). Per-barangay (142 polygons) is the next granularity push, pending OSM name reconciliation.</p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-ink-900 mt-8 mb-3">Inputs</h2>
    <p class="mb-3">Five canonical canopy / land-cover datasets, all pulled via Google Earth Engine or AWS Open Data, all bit-exact reproducible from the committed manifests:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 text-sm">
      <li><strong>Sentinel-2 L2A</strong> via <code>COPERNICUS/S2_SR_HARMONIZED</code>. Annual median composites 2019 to 2026, cloud-masked at s2cloudless probability &lt; 40, exported at 30 m to match Hansen's grid.</li>
      <li><strong>Hansen Global Forest Change v1.13</strong> via <code>UMD/hansen/global_forest_change_2025_v1_13</code>. Year-2000 baseline (treecover2000), 2001-2025 annual loss (lossyear), 2000-2012 binary gain. 30 m native.</li>
      <li><strong>ESA WorldCover v200</strong> via <code>ESA/WorldCover/v200</code>. 2021 single-epoch, 10 m class-10 = trees. Independent cross-check.</li>
      <li><strong>Dynamic World v1</strong> via <code>GOOGLE/DYNAMICWORLD/V1</code>. Annual median <code>trees</code> probability 2019 to 2026, downsampled to 30 m for the shared GEE 50 MB sync-URL limit.</li>
      <li><strong>Meta Canopy Height v2</strong> from <code>s3://dataforgood-fb-data/forests/v1/alsgedi_global_v6_float/chm/</code>. 1 m height truth (source imagery 2018-2020), Bing-style quadkey tiles, downloaded for the 4 zoom-9 tiles overlapping NCR, mosaicked, reprojected EPSG:3857 to EPSG:4326.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-xl text-ink-900 mt-8 mb-3">NDVI threshold</h2>
    <p class="mb-3">For each year, we compute NDVI = (NIR - RED) / (NIR + RED) per pixel from the Sentinel-2 composite. A binary canopy mask is derived by thresholding NDVI &ge; T, where T is calibrated against Meta canopy height v2.</p>
    <p class="mb-3">Calibration is F1-maximising over a 0.40 to 0.70 sweep, with a recall floor of 0.85 against Meta height &gt; 5 m. The sweep table lives at <code>data/calibration_report.json</code>. The result is documented in <code>BENCHMARKS.md</code>.</p>
    <p class="mb-3"><strong>Honesty caveat:</strong> Meta v2's source imagery is 80 percent from 2018-2020, so the calibration layer is a ~2019 truth, not a 2026 truth. We treat NDVI-vs-Meta agreement as a constant offset and apply the same threshold to every year. A future revision can introduce a per-year calibration once GEDI L2A monthly RH98 spot-truth is integrated.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl text-ink-900 mt-8 mb-3">Per-LGU aggregation</h2>
    <p class="mb-3">LGU polygons come from OpenStreetMap admin-level=6 relations for the 17 NCR LGUs (16 cities + Pateros). Each year's canopy mask is masked by each LGU polygon; canopy hectares are computed by multiplying pixel count by the latitude-corrected pixel area (cos(14.6 deg)) and dividing by 100 (km^2 -&gt; ha). The result is the per-LGU CSV <code>data/per_lgu/per_lgu_canopy_2019_2026.csv</code>, the hash-verified canonical artifact.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl text-ink-900 mt-8 mb-3">Reconciliation against the four public 2024+ figures</h2>
    <p class="mb-3">The four 2024+ NCR canopy figures in public circulation disagree by roughly 50 percent for the same area:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 text-sm">
      <li><strong>DENR FMB</strong> (cited in news and EJN): 6 percent / 3,565 hectares. Source document not in public 2024+ reports as of 2026-05-26.</li>
      <li><strong>Global Forest Watch</strong> dashboard PHL/47: 2.3 kha / 4.0 percent.</li>
      <li><strong>Earth Journalism Network</strong> 2024 (DENR-sourced "open forest"): 2,071 ha in 2020. Different definition.</li>
      <li><strong>ScienceKonek 2024 map</strong>: referenced by RadarPH May 2026; raster + methodology not publicly findable.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mb-3">Leaves.PH publishes a fifth, fully reproducible 2026 number with the methodology committed. The map page's headline strip reconciles all four.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl text-ink-900 mt-8 mb-3">Known limitations</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 text-sm">
      <li>30 m output resolution (matched to Hansen; trades off some urban-tree detail).</li>
      <li>Calibration epoch is ~2019 (Meta source imagery); the same threshold is applied to every year 2019 to 2026.</li>
      <li>Hansen 30 m misses small-scale urban tree-cutting events (e.g. the 225 SALEX trees in May 2026 will not appear in the global Hansen product until at least the next Hansen release).</li>
      <li>Dynamic World probability values reflect model confidence, not ground truth.</li>
      <li>Per-LGU only; per-barangay is the next granularity push.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-xl text-ink-900 mt-8 mb-3">Reproduce locally</h2>
    <pre class="bg-paper-alt p-4 rounded text-sm overflow-x-auto">git clone https://github.com/xmpuspus/leaves-ph
cd leaves-ph
python3 -m venv .venv &amp;&amp; source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
earthengine authenticate   # one-time interactive
make fetch                 # ~30 min GEE + AWS
make calibrate             # tunes the NDVI threshold against Meta
make compute               # per-year canopy mask + per-LGU CSV
make verify                # release gate</pre>

    <p class="text-sm text-ink-500 mt-6">Full prior-work review and dataset attribution: <a href="https://github.com/xmpuspus/leaves-ph/blob/main/docs/research/prior-work.md" class="no-underline text-accent-steel">docs/research/prior-work.md</a>. License: code MIT, data CC-BY-4.0.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
